# MiFichaMed – AI Context

## Overview
MiFichaMed is a medical tracking backend built with FastAPI.

Users can:
- Track conditions
- Track symptoms with daily severity
- Track treatments, medications, surgeries, allergies
- View a dashboard summary

Auth is JWT-based.

---

## Auth

### Login
POST /auth/login

Form-data:
- username (email)
- password

Response:
{
  "access_token": string,
  "refresh_token": string,
  "token_type": "bearer"
}

### Auth usage
All protected endpoints require:

Authorization: Bearer <access_token>

---

## Core Domain Model

### User
- id
- email

---

### UserProfile
- full_name
- birth_date
- sex
- weight
- height

---

### Condition System

UserCondition
- id
- condition_id
- status (active | chronic | resolved | remission)
- notes

ConditionTreatment
- medication_id
- dosage
- frequency

---

### Symptom System (IMPORTANT)

This is the most complex part of the app.

#### UserSymptom
Represents a symptom tracked by the user.

- id
- symptom_id
- severity (current, derived from latest daily)
- start_date

#### UserSymptomDaily
Represents severity per day.

- id
- user_symptom_id
- date
- severity (1–10)
- notes

### Key Logic

- Each symptom has MANY daily records
- Latest daily record updates current severity
- Deleting latest daily recalculates severity

👉 This means frontend must treat:
- "current severity" as derived state
- daily records as source of truth

---

### Allergy System

UserAllergy
- allergy_id OR name (can create custom)
- status (active | remission)
- start_date
- end_date
- notes

---

### Surgery System

UserSurgery
- surgery_id OR name (custom allowed)
- user_condition_id (optional)
- surgery_date
- status
- notes

---

## API Structure

### Symptoms

GET /user-symptoms  
POST /user-symptoms  
PATCH /user-symptoms/{id}  
DELETE /user-symptoms/{id}

---

### Symptom Daily

GET /user-symptoms/{id}/daily  
POST /user-symptoms/{id}/daily  
PATCH /user-symptoms/{id}/daily/{daily_id}  
DELETE /user-symptoms/{id}/daily/{daily_id}

---

### Conditions

GET /user-conditions  
POST /user-conditions  

---

### Treatments

GET /condition-treatments  
POST /condition-treatments  

---

### Allergies

GET /user-allergies  
POST /user-allergies  
PATCH /user-allergies/{id}  
DELETE /user-allergies/{id}

---

### Surgeries

GET /user-surgeries  
POST /user-surgeries  
PATCH /user-surgeries/{id}  
DELETE /user-surgeries/{id}

---

### Profile

GET /user-profile  
POST /user-profile  
PATCH /user-profile  

---

### Dashboard

GET /dashboard

Returns:
{
  profile,
  active_conditions[],
  active_symptoms[]
}

---

## UI Expectations (IMPORTANT FOR FRONTEND AI)

### Symptom UI

Frontend should support:

1. Symptom list
2. Symptom detail view
3. Daily tracking UI (calendar-like)

Behavior:
- Selecting a day loads its severity
- Updating slider updates that day's record
- New day = new daily record

---

### Key UX Pattern

For symptoms:

- Horizontal date selector (like calendar strip)
- Slider for severity (1–10)
- Notes per day

---

## Backend Patterns

### Catalog + Custom Entries

Many entities support:
- predefined catalog
- user-created custom entries

Pattern:
- send `id` OR `name`
- backend creates catalog entry if needed

---

## Important Constraints

- All data is user-scoped (multi-tenant)
- Must always send JWT
- Some endpoints return 404 if not owned

---

## What the AI SHOULD DO

When generating frontend:

- Use React (or Next.js)
- Use hooks per feature (symptoms, conditions, etc.)
- Separate:
  - services (API calls)
  - hooks (state)
  - components (UI)

---

## Known Gaps / Assumptions

- No pagination handling yet in frontend
- No caching layer
- No optimistic updates implemented

---

## Priority Features for Frontend

1. Symptom tracking (HIGH PRIORITY)
2. Dashboard
3. Conditions + treatments
4. Profile

---

## Example Flow (Symptom)

1. GET /user-symptoms
2. User selects one
3. GET /user-symptoms/{id}/daily
4. User selects date
5. PATCH /daily/{id} OR POST new

---
